w back. We now know that the liver can regenerate, but were the ancient Greeks aware of this quality? The myth of Prometheus has been a source of inspiration for many visual artists over the centuries. In this book, the medical history of the liver is traced through the ages through an examination of historical texts on the organ's functions and properties, parallel to the art movements in which the fascinating iconography of Prometheus is reviewed. The book offers a surprising interplay of art and medicine, placing emphasis on the unique morphology of the liver.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 4aAncient Greek religion and mythology. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aHepatology. 4aHistory of Science and Medicine. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHuman figures depicted in art. 4aMythology. 7aART / Subjects & Themes / General.2bisacsh  aPrometheus, myth, art, liver, medicine.1 aGulik, Merel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRosmalen, Belle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048557417zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048557417/original  a978-3-11-076700-1 DG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2b2022  a978-3-11-076709-4 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA